    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-10T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-10T10:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EAC/198: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-10T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 10, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 10—4:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4655. Comea 61. At an informal meeting of the European Advisory Commission
                    yesterday the draft of surrender terms for Germany was accepted by the three
                    representatives. Some minor changes were made in the text and the language has
                    been much improved. At the insistence of the other representatives it was
                    decided that before the draft is finally recommended to the three Governments,
                    certain points are first to be disposed of including the question of
                    consultation with other Allied Governments and the general outline of
                    occupation. Discussion has shown progress toward agreement on these points and
                    we will continue our work on Monday.<note n="74" xml:id="d118fn74">June
                        12.</note> The Russian delegation has agreed to discuss control machinery
                    for Germany at an early date. They are also completing their drafts of the
                    proclamations and orders which together with those drafted by ourselves and by
                    the British will be studied by experts of the three delegations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
